Kafka at the Core of any Digital Twins Architecture

Ran Katzir (Valerann CTO: Digital Twins for ITS)

·

Follow

6 min read
·
Jun 3, 2023

I’ve always struggled with the exact definition of digital twins. Like any trend, every company interprets it to fit its strategy and interests. So I feel that I must start with my definition of digital twin, to establish some common grounds.

Digital Twin is a digital representation of a physical asset, it includes the physical properties of the asset, the environment that it operates in, and its internal state in real-time.

Digital twins can be used to monitor the state of the asset, but also to predict future behavior, and control the asset remotely.

As someone who is in the tech industry for more than 30 years, the first time that I heard of Digital Twins, I said. OK, what’s new? We did monitoring 50 years ago when we landed a man on the moon 🤷‍♂️

Apollo Mission Control Room: Is this a digital twin?

So, really what’s new?

Well, honestly the concept is the same but compared to 50 years ago, the technology and the tools are so much better and within reach. You don’t have to be NASA to have a digital twin of your assets. Whether this is a transportation infrastructure, a utility plant, your house, or a whole city.

Today we have Big Data, Cloud, AI, IoT sensors, HD CCTV cameras, and millions of DevOps, Backend, and Frontend engineers ready and eager to implement it for you.

But can you trust them to build it the right way?

Any discussion on digital architecture needs to first address the biggest fear that CIOs and CEOs face. Would it last for at least 5–10 years? An architecture that goes through major revolutions every 1–2 years is not an architecture, it’s chaos. Digital architecture, just like building architecture, or landscape architecture, needs to last for many years and should be still relevant, resilient, adaptable, affordable, and able to grow.

So what internal structure can make digital twins relevant, resilient, adaptable, and scalable for the next 5–10 years?

I mentioned earlier that there are so many new technologies and tools available today to build new products and systems. What I didn’t mention, is that we have too many 😰. Which database should we use? Architecture can’t just specify concepts and patterns. In the end, specific components and protocols need to be chosen. So how do we make this crucial decision?

We need to map the requirements first.

Digital Twins Technical Requirements:

  • Realtime: Data needs to reach the operator with sub-second latency
  • Resilient: The system needs to be highly available and secured and endure both a small-scale failure and a large-scale disaster. Monitored 24/7
  • Spatial-temporal: Data need to relate to a specific time and physical location.
  • Consistent Ontology and units: We don’t want failures like Ariane 5
  • Source: Ability to ingest various types of data: structured and unstructured, sensor data, text files, and videos, real-time, batch, and historical through various protocols (HTTP, MQTT, TCP, REST, SOAP), but also sometimes industrial protocols such as Provibus and Modbus.
  • Sink: Ability to expose the data via various channels: API, Pub/Sub feeds, SQL, Analytic tools, maps, 3D, mobile apps, social media
  • Transform Ability to include scalable real-time processing pipelines that convert the raw data into meaningful and valuable insights using AI, machine learning, time series analysis, geospatial analysis, and other scientific techniques.

Digital Twins Non-Technical Requirements:

  • Adaptable: Easy to add new data sources, new processing capabilities, new components to model, or new user interfaces.
  • Safe: You want to make sure that no accidental/unapproved/malicious command is sent to the field devices
  • Secured: Security serves multiple purposes: resilience, safety, privacy, IP protection, company brand, etc…
  • Decoupled and modularity: Clear separation of concerns and functionality
  • Affordable: Setup cost + operation cost
  • Global: In many cases, data needs to come from multiple regions around the world.
  • Longevity: 5–10 years
  • FAIR: Data should be Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, Reusable
  • Upgradeable: no risk of upgrade or repair for both infrastructure components and system components, without downtime

Solution Guidelines

To address some of the above concerns, I propose the following guidelines:

  • The solution should be based on open-source cloud-agnostic components. Open source components became over the last years the new industry standards. Even though all the cloud providers attempted to pull developers into their own closed solutions, they realized eventually that if they don’t provide a managed open source-based solution like Kubernetes, Postgres, or Kafka, they will be out of the game. The fact that you can deploy open-source solutions on-premise is also a very attractive benefit. And finally, open-source solutions historically have a higher chance to last 5–10 years while still being maintained by a large community.
  • Kafka should be used as the integration middleware between services. Kafka is open-source, real-time, resilient, and scalable, and even though it’s hard to tune, it’s the only solution that can deliver the desired requirements.
  • Clearly define in advance the ontology, data models, and schema. Changing the data model along the way is hard. If there are industry standards, use them!
  • Use agent base model: Services should act as agents with roles: source services, transform services (stateless /stateful), and sink services.
  • Break processing into small steps, each in its own agent. Complex processing can create many issues: You can’t reuse intermediate results for other needs, you don’t have good observability of the process, they are harder to debug, and inefficient to scale.
  • Sink all the live Kafka topics into your data warehouse. This will help you with complex analytics and will add visibility and auditing to your system health. Don’t attempt to perform extensive analytics on top of Kafka with technologies such as ksqlDB. Use the right tool for the right job.
  • Use multi-tier data access: real-time (sub-second latency on incoming data), Fast analytics / Data Warehouse (1–5 seconds over a period of weeks-months), Slow analytics / Big Data (minutes latency over a period of years). Cold archive.

Conclusions

  • Coming up with the right architecture for Digital Twins is hard
  • Implementing it yourself is harder (And maintaining it for 5–10 years). Don’t be tempted to think that it’s easy. It’s going to be very hard and will require many resources. Even though it takes 10 seconds to start a database in the cloud, it takes years to build a reliable and resilient system around it.
  • Probably, you are trying to build something that similar organizations like yours have already built or going to build. In the end, a road is a road, a factory is a factory, a building is a building. Your needs are not unique to you. Maybe there is a solution out there that does 90% of what you need.

So you end up with a very important strategic question: Make (or outsource) or Buy (a product/platform)?

The best of all worlds would be, in my opinion, to find a digital twin product that internally uses Kafka, and agree on a shared responsibility model, where you as a client, can connect to internal topics, and add additional services and data sources to the system.

Whatever you decide, make sure that you have a strong and experienced architect that will ask the right questions, and won’t get you into a never-ending adventure.

Personal preference…

I’ve tried to keep this article neutral as much as I can, even though obviously it includes my bias. Personally, I would also recommend:

  • To use Python as the main programming language.
  • To use Postgres as a Data warehouse.
  • To prefer fuzzy logic over boolean logic
